<H2><U>
<a name="figures">Important Sioux Mythological Figures</a>
</u></H2>

<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/iktomi.htm">Iktomi</font></a></U></B></I> (also spelled Unktomi or Inktomi,
depending on dialect.)
The trickster figure of Lakota and Dakota Sioux myths. His name literally means "spider" and he is sometimes called Spider or Spider-Man in English, but
he is usually depicted as a human man in Sioux legends. Like other Plains Indian trickster figures, Iktomi is a negative role model who behaves
as socially inappropriately as possible by Sioux standards. Most Sioux stories about Iktomi are consequently very funny, ranging from light-hearted fables
about buffoonish behavior to ribald jokes. But sometimes Iktomi's misbehavior is more serious and violent, and the stories become cautionary tales about
the dangers of the world.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/legends-coyote.htm">Coyote</font></a></U></B></I> (Mica or Maca, in the Sioux languages.)
Coyote is another traditional trickster figure of Sioux mythology, and indeed some of the same stories are told with either Iktomi or Coyote
as the protagonist. Coyote is sometimes anthropomorphized into human form and other times depicted in the shape of an actual coyote 
(sometimes both within a single story.) Many Sioux stories about Coyote are sexual in nature (we have avoided posting these stories here due to
the large number of children who use our website, but adult students of folklore can consult the excellent book
<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140277714/natilangofthe-20">American Indian Trickster Tales</a> to
learn more about that aspect of Sioux folklore.)
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/wakan-tanka.htm">Wakan Tanka</font></a></U></B></I>:
The great Creator power of Sioux cosmology. Literally it means "Great Mystery." Originally Wakan-Tanka was an abstract creative
force who was never personified in Sioux legends, but after the introduction of Christianity some Native people began
using it as the Sioux name of God.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/white-buffalo-woman.htm">White Buffalo Calf Woman</font></a></U></B></I> (Ptesan-Wi):
A sacred culture hero of the Sioux tribes. She brought the sacred pipe to the Sioux people, and taught them many of the arts of civilization. 
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/thunderer.htm">Thunderer</font></a></U></B></I> (Wakinyan):
Known in English as the Thunderer or the Thunderbird, Wakinyan is a powerful sky spirit of Sioux Indian legends.
Wakinyan has the form of a giant bird, with wings that make the sound of thunder and eyes that shoot
lightning. The Sioux Thunderbird is the mortal enemy of the horned serpent Unktehi.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/unktehila.htm">Unktehi</font></a></U></B></I>:
The great horned serpent of Sioux mythology, mortal enemy of the Thunderbird.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/inyan.htm">Inyan</font></a></U></B></I>:
Primordial stone spirit of Sioux mythology.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/rabbit-boy.htm">Rabbit Boy</font></a></U></B></I>:
A folk hero of Sioux mythology, born from a clot of blood and raised by rabbits.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/two-face.htm">Double Face</font></a></U></B></I></a> (Hestovatohkeo'o):
A malevolent monster resembling a man with a second face on the back of his head. According to Lakota and Dakota folklore, a person who makes eye contact 
with this second face will be murdered by the monster, who tries many ploys to try to get victims to look at him.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/canotila.htm">Canoti</font></a></U></B></I>:
Fairy-like little people of Sioux folklore. 
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U><A href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/chiye-tanka.htm">Chiye-Tanka</font></a></U></B></I>:
Bigfoot-like woodland spirit of Sioux folklore.

<H2><U>
<a name="tribes">Sioux Indian Folklore</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://www.gutenberg.org/files/341/341-h/341-h.htm
">Myths and Legends of the Sioux</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Online book of Dakota legends recorded in the early 1900's.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.sacred-texts.com/nam/oil.htm
">Zitkala-Sa's Book of Sioux Legends</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Classic collection of Lakota legends told by author Zitkala-Sa in 1901.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021740/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux4.htm
">Remaking the World</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*">  <b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021317/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux14.htm
">How The Sioux Came To Be</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Sioux myths about the Great Flood.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/tetongho.htm
">A Teton Ghost Story</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota story about a man who married a ghost woman.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021730/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux2.htm
">How Grandfather Peyote Came to the People</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota myth about the origins of the peyote religion.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021755/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux8.htm
">The Snake Brothers</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Sioux legend about three men who were turned into snakes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021332/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux9.htm
">The Man Who Was Afraid of Nothing</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A funny Lakota ghost story.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021700/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux10.htm
">The Ghost Wife</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Sioux story about a man who brought his wife back from the land of the dead.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021710/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux13.htm
">Uncegila's Seventh Spot</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Indian legend about the water monster Uncegila.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021322/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux15.htm
">Stone Boy</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legend about a young hero born from a rock.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021322/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux16.htm
">Wakinyan Tanka, the Great Thunderbird</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Sioux legends about thunderbirds.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20100412123606/http://home.online.no/~arnfin/native/lore/leg223.htm
">A Legend Of Devil's Tower</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Brule Sioux legend about the origin of the Devil's Tower landform.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021750/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux7.htm
">The Vision Quest</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Indian story about a young man learning humility.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021745/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux5.htm
">Tatanka Iyotake's Dancing Horse</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legends about the death of the great leader Sitting Bull.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121023021311/http://pyramidmesa.com/bsioux11.htm
">The Dogs hold an Election</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Humorous Lakota story about how dogs choose their leaders.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.bigorrin.org/archive120.htm
">Sioux Creation Myth</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Dakota story of the origin of the world.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.ilhawaii.net/~stony/lore30.html
">Origin of the Lakota Peace Pipe</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota myth of the White Buffalo Woman and the sacred pipe.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.ilhawaii.net/~stony/lore129.html
">The Resuscitation of the Only Daughter</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Sioux legend about a girl who came back from the dead.

<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/Iktome-Coyote-And-The-Rock-Sioux.html
">Coyote, Iktome, and Rock</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota version of a classic Plains Indian legend about Coyote trying to take back a gift to the spirits.

<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121114065934/http://pyramidmesa.com/wrsioux1.htm
">Brave Woman Counts Coup</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legend about a female warrior who led her people to victory.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121114065923/http://pyramidmesa.com/wrsioux4.htm
">Rabbit Boy</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legend about Iktome unsuccessfully trying to murder a powerful young hero.

<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://curtis.library.northwestern.edu/curtis/viewPage.cgi?showp=1&size=2&id=nai.03.book.00000181&volume=3
">Weyota and Iktomi</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota folktales about Blood-Clot Boy.

<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121114065912/http://pyramidmesa.com/wrsioux5.htm
">Spotted Eagle and Black Crow</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legend about an abandoned warrior saved by a family of eagles.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/How-The-Crow-Came-To-Be-Black-Sioux.html
">How The Crow Came To Be Black</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Brule Sioux legend about a nosy crow punished for his interference with a hunter.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20100104091532/http://www.rickwalton.com/folktale/sioux05.htm
">The Rabbit and the Elk</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Sioux story about Elk playing a trick on Rabbit.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121114065918/http://pyramidmesa.com/wrsioux2.htm
">Chief Roman Nose Loses His Medicine</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota legend about the death of Cheyenne chief Roman Nose.

<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121114065928/http://pyramidmesa.com/wrsioux3.htm
">The End of the World</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lakota Sioux myth about the prophecied end of the world.

<BR>

<H2><U>
<a name="books">Recommended Books on Sioux Mythology</a>
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0806132248/natilangofthe-20
">The Sons of the Wind: The Sacred Stories of the Lakota</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Collection of Sioux legends told by a Lakota author.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0803298609/natilangofthe-20
">Lakota Myth</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Book on traditional Lakota mythology, religion, and ritual.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0689816839/natilangofthe-20
">Love Flute</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Picture book illustrating the Sioux legend of how the elks brought the first courting flute.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/157098235X/natilangofthe-20
">Heetunka's Harvest</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Children's storybook based on the Dakota legend of the bean mice.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0689820860/natilangofthe-20
">Adopted by the Eagles</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0823410072/natilangofthe-20
">Spotted Eagle and Black Crow</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Two illustrated children's books based on Sioux Indian myths about a betrayed hunter rescued by eagles.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0531070441/natilangofthe-20
">Iktomi and the Ducks</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0531070239/natilangofthe-20
">Iktomi and the Boulder</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0531070298/natilangofthe-20
">Iktomi and the Berries</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lively retellings of three Sioux tales about the trickster Iktomi.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0064436195/natilangofthe-20
">Moonstick: The Seasons of the Sioux</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Picture book based on the traditional names of moons in the Sioux calendar system.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140277714/natilangofthe-20
">American Indian Trickster Tales</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Compilation of more than a hundred stories about Iktomi, Coyote, and other Native American tricksters.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
(Use discretion sharing these with kids as some of the stories contain adult humor.)
